title: Treesearch Farms' uniqueness withstanding test of time
author: Landan Kuhlmann
excerpt: For Treesearch Farms and owner Heidi Sheesley, it's all about being the one that stands out from the crowd. Anyone can sell plants, she said, but for her it's always
summary:
For Treesearch Farms and owner Heidi Sheesley, it's all about being the one that stands out from the crowd. Anyone can sell plants, she said, but for her it's always been about the education and success of those she sells to.
'I want people to succeed with their plants – if they're successful they'll come back and trying something else. That gives me the most pleasure,' she said. 'We're not the typical business – making money is important, but it's more than that.'
Sheesley began Treesearch Farms back in 1983, after working at an indoor plant nursery for several years.

title: Bystander at Nashville school shooting scene interrupts live TV report with impassioned speech

summary:
A bystander at the Nashville school shooting took the mic at a live cross to plea for gun safety laws after she and her son survived a mass shooting last July.
Mother Ashbey Beasley told those gathered that she has been lobbying in Washington DC and has met with more than 130 lawmakers.
'How is this still happening? How are our children still dying and why are we failing them,' she questioned, in a passionate speech.
'Aren't you guys tired of this? Aren't you sick of it?' Beasley added, addressing the TV crew.

China's new premier, Li Qiang, has offered a hearty welcome to foreign companies in an effort to arrest a slump in business confidence that has exacerbated the country's economic woes.

title: Plan for higher rates on consumer loans moves ahead
author: News Service
excerpt: The bill has drawn opposition from groups concerned about the rate hike.
summary:
A House panel Monday approved a bill that would increase the maximum interest rate on consumer finance loans, while placing additional requirements on the industry.

The House Insurance & Banking Subcommittee unanimously backed the bill (HB 1267), sponsored by Rep. Juan Alfonso Fernandez-Barquin, R-Miami-Dade County.

Under current law, consumer-finance loan companies can charge 30 percent annual interest on the first $3,000 of principal amounts, 24 percent on amounts between $3,000 and $4,000 and 18 percent on amounts between $4,000 and $25,000.

author: Nick Blank
excerpt: The local developer plans to begin construction by the end of the year.
summary:
A $65 million Corner Lot apartment project in North Jacksonville took a step on Monday toward receiving a $7.5 million property tax rebate.

Corner Lot, through Springfield MF Partners LLC, is seeking a rebate on property taxes from the city of up to $7.5 million. The incentive package would shave off 75% of the increase in real and personal property taxes generated by improvements at the project site for 15 years.

The package was passed by the Mayor's Budget Review Committee, a step before introducing legislation for the deal is introduced to the City Council on April 11.
